SIMPLE: measles
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Measles
<hw>Mea"sles</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From 1st
<er>Measle</er>.]</ety> <def>Leprosy; also, a leper.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measles</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Measles
<hw>Mea"sles</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> in form, but used as
<xex>singular</xex> in senses 1, 2, & 3.</plu> <ety>[D.
<ets>mazelen</ets>; akin to G. <ets>masern</ets>, pl., and E.
<ets>mazer</ets>, and orig. meaning, little spots. See
<er>Mazer</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A contagious viral febrile
disorder commencing with catarrhal symptoms, and marked by the
appearance on the third day of an eruption of distinct red circular
spots, which coalesce in a crescentic form, are slightly raised above
the surface, and after the fourth day of the eruption gradually decline;
rubeola. It is a common childhood disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Measles</qex> commences with the ordinary symptoms of
fever.</q> <rj><qau>Am. Cyc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 906 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Veter. Med.)</fld> <def>A disease of cattle and
swine in which the flesh is filled with the embryos of different
varieties of the tapeworm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A disease of trees.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The larvae of
any tapeworm (<gen>Taenia</gen>) in the cysticercus stage, when
contained in meat. Called also <altname>bladder
worms</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>German measles</b></col> <cd>A mild contagious viral
disease, which may cause birth defects if contracted by a pregnant woman
during early pregnancy; also called
<altname>rubella</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>measly</ent>⟦br⟧
